{"amendments":[{"body":"`src/contexts/milestone_record/service.rs:417-474` seals the lineage row before updating the snapshot or journal, but `src/adapters/fs.rs:2545-2556` rejects any later finalize on an already-terminal entry. If `write_snapshot` or `append_event` fails after the row update, retrying `record_bead_completion`/`update_task_run` can no longer repair the snapshot/journal drift, so a transient I/O failure leaves milestone state permanently inconsistent unless `task-runs.ndjson` is edited manually. Make completion idempotent for the same terminal payload, or defer sealing the lineage row until the rest of the milestone state is durable.","rationale":"This turns a partial write into an unrecoverable corruption path, which is a real robustness regression in the new update flow."},{"body":"`src/contexts/milestone_record/service.rs:305-308` moves a started bead into `MilestoneStatus::Active`, but `src/contexts/milestone_record/service.rs:448-456` clears `active_bead` on completion without changing `status` or re-validating. `src/contexts/milestone_record/model.rs:172-176` explicitly defines `status == Active && active_bead == None` as inconsistent, so every normal completion now persists a snapshot that violates the model invariant. Completion needs to transition out of `Active` (or otherwise preserve the invariant) before writing the snapshot.","rationale":"This is a direct correctness bug in the touched completion path: persisted milestone snapshots become semantically invalid after a bead finishes."}],"summary":"Reviewed the milestone lineage changes and ran the `contexts::milestone_record` tests. I found two correctness issues in the completion path: finalize is not retry-safe after partial failures, and completed snapshots still violate the `Active`/`active_bead` invariant."}